\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ehrenfest
\end_layout

\end_inset

For electron–radiation dynamics, Ehrenfest method combines quantum Liouville
 equation and classical electrodynamics in a mean-field approximation manner;
 the averaged quantum observable of the system represents the response to
 the classical field.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Good
\end_layout

\end_inset

One of the advantages of Ehrenfest dynamics is that, the total energy is
 conserved in a self-consistent way.
 Also, the implementation is computationally inexpensive and can be generalized
 to a large system.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
example
\end_layout

\end_inset

Recent studies have shown that Ehrenfest dynamics can capture the qualitative
 feature of absorption spectra of a two-level system, and photo-initiated
 excited dynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "li_mixed_2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
another good
\end_layout

\end_inset

The predicted emission rate is close to the correct spontaneous decay rate,
 given that the initial coherence of the system is not zero .
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
however
\end_layout

\end_inset

However, apart from known quantitative discrepancy, the current implementation
 of Ehrenfest dynamics could result in unphysical behaviors in some situations,
 such as zero electronic coherence and strong dephasing, which put a limitation
 on its applicability.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
goal
\end_layout

\end_inset

Our goal here is to investigate the origin of the failure of Ehrenfest dynamics
 by analyzing the undeyling mixed quantum–classical theory and to propose
 a new algorithm based on Ehrenfest method for electron–radiation dynamics.
\end_layout

