\begin_layout Subsubsection
Implementation in wavefunction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To implement the propagation of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EOM_Ehrenfest+R"

\end_inset

, we now consider the electronic system in a pure state, so that we have
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\rho}=\left|\psi\right\rangle \left\langle \psi\right|$
\end_inset

.
 For each time step 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

, the wavefunction can be evolved by a two-step propagation scheme:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\psi\left(t+dt\right)\right\rangle =\widehat{{\cal T}}_{0\leftarrow1}\left[k_{R}\right]\cdot e^{-i\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}}dt/\hbar}\left|\psi\left(t\right)\right\rangle .\label{eq:EhrenfestPropagation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The propagator 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}}dt/\hbar}$
\end_inset

 carries out the standard Ehrenfest dynamics with the electronic Hamiltonian
 given by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:electronic_Hamiltonian"

\end_inset

.
 The quantum transition operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{{\cal T}}_{0\leftarrow1}\left(k_{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 implement the additional population relaxation.
 Explicitly, the transition operator is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
c_{0}^{\prime}\\
c_{1}^{\prime}
\end{array}\right)=\widehat{{\cal T}}_{0\leftarrow1}\left[k_{R}\right]\left(\begin{array}{c}
c_{0}\\
c_{1}
\end{array}\right)\label{eq:TransitonOperator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
c_{0}^{\prime\prime} & = & \frac{c_{0}^{\prime}}{\left|c_{0}^{\prime}\right|}\sqrt{\left|c_{0}^{\prime}\right|^{2}+k_{R}\left|c_{1}^{\prime}\right|^{2}dt},\\
c_{1}^{\prime\prime} & = & \frac{c_{1}^{\prime}}{\left|c_{1}^{\prime}\right|}\sqrt{\left|c_{1}^{\prime}\right|^{2}-k_{R}\left|c_{1}^{\prime}\right|^{2}dt}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{0}^{\prime}=\begin{cases}
c_{0}\sqrt{1+\frac{\left|c_{1}\right|^{2}}{\left|c_{0}\right|^{2}}\left(1-e^{-k_{R}dt}\right)}, & \text{if }\left|c_{0}\right|\neq0,\\
\sqrt{1-e^{-k_{R}dt}}e^{i\theta}, & \text{if }\left|c_{0}\right|=0,
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{1}^{\prime}=c_{1}e^{-k_{R}dt/2}\approx\frac{c_{1}}{\left|c_{1}\right|}\sqrt{\left|c_{1}\right|^{2}-k_{R}\left|c_{1}\right|^{2}dt},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|c_{0}\right|\neq0$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}c_{0}^{\prime} & =c_{0}\sqrt{1+\frac{\left|c_{1}\right|^{2}}{\left|c_{0}\right|^{2}}\left(1-e^{-k_{R}dt}\right)}\\
 & \approx\frac{c_{0}}{\left|c_{0}\right|}\sqrt{\left|c_{0}\right|^{2}+k_{R}\left|c_{1}\right|^{2}dt}
\end{split}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the phase of the wavefunction is preserved by the transition operator
 in this implemtation.
 In other words, the transition operator simply transfer 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{R}\left|c_{1}\right|^{2}dt$
\end_inset

 amount of population from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 without changing the phase of the wavefunction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, it is noted that, when the density matrix of the system is only on
 the excited state (
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\rho}=\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|$
\end_inset

), i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|c_{0}\right|=0$
\end_inset

, there is a undetermined phase in the wavefunction representation, say
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =e^{i\theta}\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the transition operator is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
c_{1}^{\prime} & = & e^{i\theta}e^{-\kappa dt/2}\approx e^{i\theta}\sqrt{1-\kappa dt},\\
c_{0}^{\prime} & = & \sqrt{1-e^{-\kappa dt}}\approx\sqrt{\kappa dt},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

in which we find 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k_{Eh}}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k_{R}}=\kappa$
\end_inset

, and the additional relaxation takes full responsibility of the spontaneous
 decay.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Energy changes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the Ehrenfest propagation 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}}dt/\hbar}$
\end_inset

 together with Maxwell's equations conserves the total energy, the quantum
 transition leads to energy changes of the electronic system by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dU_{s}}{dt}=\text{Tr}\left\{ \widehat{H}_{s}{\cal L}_{R}\widehat{\rho}\right\} =-\omega_{0}k_{R}\rho_{11}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In terms of the quantum transition operator for time step 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

, the energy loss of the system is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta U_{R}=\omega_{0}k_{R}\rho_{11}dt.\label{eq:EnergyChange}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To maintain energy conservation, the energy loss has to flow into the EM
 filed in the form of light emission.
 In the following, we introduce a rescaling scheme of the EM field to make
 up for the energy loss accordingly.
\end_layout

